<div class="card mt-4">
  <div class="card-body">
    <h1 class="card-title mb-3">What to do if the lease looks incorrect</h1>
    <p>
      We understand it can be frustrating if the information shown doesn’t match your expectations.
      Here are some things to check and consider:
    </p>

    <h5 class="mt-4">1. Check the tool's data freshness</h5>
    <p>On the <a href="/app">search page</a>, you'll see the date of the last successful monthly data import from HM Land Registry. This tells you when our dataset was last updated overall.</p>

    <h5 class="mt-4">2. Check when this lease was last updated</h5>
    <p>On the lease details page, you’ll see when this specific lease record was last updated. Sometimes the lease may not change even though the monthly dataset is refreshed – that means HM Land Registry hasn’t updated that lease in their source data.</p>

    <h5 class="mt-4">3. Stay notified of changes</h5>
    <p>If this lease is important to you, you can bookmark it. If HM Land Registry update it in a future release, we’ll notify you by email. You can disable these notifications in your <a href="/profile">profile</a> at any time, and updated leases are always marked on the main app screen too.</p>

    <h5 class="mt-4">4. Still looks wrong?</h5>
    <p>It’s possible you may be looking at a different lease than intended. Postcodes can sometimes be misentered or properties split into separate records. Try searching again by address e.g. <i>122 Manchester Road</i>.</p>

    <h5 class="mt-4">5. Next steps</h5>
    <p>If the lease data still appears incorrect and our tool is up to date, the next step is to 
      <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/contact-hm-land-registry" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
        contact HM Land Registry<span class="visually-hidden">(opens in a new tab)</span>
        <i class="bi bi-box-arrow-up-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>
      </a>
    .</p>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center mt-3">
    <a href="<%= uid ? `/app/lease/${uid}` : '/app' %>" class="btn btn-secondary">
        Back to <%= uid ? 'Lease' : 'Search' %>
    </a>
  </div>
  </div>


</div>
